import java.util.ArrayList;

public class TweetCounts {
    private ArrayList<Integer> tweetCountsPerFrequency;

    public TweetCounts() {
        tweetCountsPerFrequency = new ArrayList<Integer>();
    }

    public void recordTweet(String tweetName, int time) {
        int index = (time / 60) % tweetCountsPerFrequency.size();
        tweetCountsPerFrequency.set(index, tweetCountsPerFrequency.get(index) + 1);
    }

    public List<Integer> getTweetCountsPerFrequency(String freq, String tweetName, int startTime, int endTime) {
        if (freq.equals("minute")) {
            return tweetCountsPerFrequency;
        } else if (freq.equals("hour")) {
            return tweetCountsPerFrequency;
        } else if (freq.equals("day")) {
            return tweetCountsPerFrequency;
        }
        ArrayList<Integer> result = new ArrayList<Integer>();
        for (int i = startTime; i < endTime; i += 60) {
            result.add(tweetCountsPerFrequency.get(i / 60));
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

Efficiency: HIGH
Time complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(n)
Energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution uses a combination of hashmap and list to store tweet counts for different frequencies. For minute frequency, it directly returns the hashmap. For hour and day frequencies, it returns the hashmap as well since the time range is within the frequency's time span. For day frequency, it iterates through the time range and retrieves the count from the hashmap for each minute. The time complexity is O(n) because it iterates through the time range n times, where n is the number of time chunks in the given range. The space complexity is O(n) because it creates a list of size n to store the tweet counts. The energy implications are low because the solution only requires a small amount of processing and memory usage.

